\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 How to use the Interpreter\

\f1\b0\fs24 
\
This document is OSX specific. For the linux emacs sclang interface please see  linux specific documentation.\
\
You can execute any single line expression by clicking anywhere in that line and pressing the 
\f0\b 'Enter'
\f1\b0  key.\

\f0\b Note that the 'Enter' key is not the same key as 'Return'.\

\f1\b0 
\
You will need to start the default server before you can hear any examples. By convention the default server is assigned to the interpreter variable 's'. (At startup the default will be the localhost server.) You can start the server app by pressing the 'Boot' button on the localhost server window, or you can do it in code:\

\f2\fs18 \
\cf2 // execute these lines one at a time by placing the cursor on the line and then pressing 'enter'\
\cf3 \
s.boot; \cf2 // this boots the default Server. Watch the post window and server window for the result\
\
// once that's done execute this to make a sound\cf3 \
\{ \cf4 FSinOsc\cf3 .ar(800, 0.1) \}.play;
\fs24 \cf0 \

\f1 \
(Press and hold Cmd (the Apple key) and then press period to stop the sound started above.)\
\
In the help files all executable fragments are written in the 
\f2 Monaco
\f1  font.\
\
If an expression has multiple lines you can select all of the lines before typing 'Enter'.\
\

\f2\fs18 \cf5 // Select all three of the following lines and press 'Enter':\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf3 w = \cf4 SCWindow\cf3 .new(\cf6 "Fading"\cf3 ).front;\
r = \cf4 Routine\cf3 (\{ 200.do(\{\cf4 |i|\cf3  w.alpha = 1 - (i * 0.005); 0.005.wait;\}); w.close; \});\
\cf4 AppClock\cf3 .play(r);
