Some examples do require lines to be executed one at a time, or certain lines to be executed first. By far the most common case of this is booting the server app, as we did at the top of the page. Until the server has completed booting, no sound producing code will work.\
\
However, most of the examples included with the app have parentheses around lines of code which should be executed at the same time. (This is a convention which should be followed in your own code.) This allows you to double click to the right of the open paren and select the entire expression. Then press 'enter'.\

\fs18 \

\f2 (\
\cf5 // ^^^^^^^^ double click above this line ^^^^^^^^\
\cf0 play(\{\
\cf5 // Three patches in one...\
\cf0 n = 5;	\cf5 // number of strings\
\cf0 b = [	\cf5 // array of possible impulse excitation behaviours\
\cf0 		\{ \cf7 Impulse\cf0 .ar(2 + 0.2.rand, 0.3) \}, \cf5 // slow phasing\
\cf0 		\{ \cf7 Dust\cf0 .ar(0.5, 0.3) \},	\cf5 // "wind chimes"\
\cf0 		\{ \cf7 Impulse\cf0 .ar(\cf7 SinOsc\cf0 .kr(0.05+0.1.rand, 2pi.rand, 5, 5.2), 0.3) \} \cf5 // races\
\cf0 	].choose;		\cf5 // choose one at random to use for all voices\
\cf7 Mix\cf0 .new(\
	\cf7 Array\cf0 .fill(n, \{	\cf5 // n strings tuned randomly to MIDI keys 60-90\
\cf0 		\cf7 var\cf0  delayTime;\
		\cf5 // calculate delay based on a random note\
\cf0 		delayTime = 1 / (60 + 30.rand).midicps; \
		\cf7 Pan2\cf0 .ar(\
			\cf7 CombL\cf0 .ar(		\cf5 // used as a string resonator\
\cf0 				\cf7 Decay\cf0 .ar(		\cf5 // decaying envelope for noise\
\cf0 					b.value,				\cf5 // instantiate an exciter\
\cf0 					0.04,				\cf5 // decay time of excitation\
